WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.600
Our RStudio Cloud currently supports three project types, RStudio Projects, Projects

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:12.980
from a Git Repository, and our newest feature, Jupyter Projects.

00:00:12.980 --> 00:00:17.600
This means that as instructors, we have a good deal of flexibility over the coding environment

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:22.760
we create for our learners, and that we can teach using both R and Python within the same

00:00:22.760 --> 00:00:26.320
cloud-based environment.

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:30.240
We can access each of these project types by clicking on the arrow in the right-hand

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:33.060
side of the New Projects button.

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:38.540
When we select RStudio Project, we're taken to a new, untitled project within the RStudio

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:49.759
IDE.

00:00:49.759 --> 00:00:54.080
When we select Jupyter Project, we're taken to a new, untitled project that gives us all

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:59.020
of the same functionality we expect from within a Jupyter Project, including the ability

00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:17.279
to upload files, as well as create new Python notebooks using specific versions of Python.

00:01:17.279 --> 00:01:22.419
We can also clone a new RStudio or Jupyter Project from a Git Repository.

00:01:22.419 --> 00:01:27.699
For RStudio Projects, we simply provide the URL of the corresponding Git Repository, while

00:01:27.699 --> 00:01:32.540
for Jupyter, we can accomplish this by cloning our repository from a new terminal within

00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:37.059
a Jupyter Project on RStudio Cloud.

00:01:37.059 --> 00:01:41.300
RStudio support for Jupyter Projects is exciting, although at the time of this recording, the

00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:43.099
feature is still in beta.

00:01:43.099 --> 00:01:46.900
We would love to hear your feedback, and you can always reach out to us on the community

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:50.500
forums at community.rstudio.com.

